            <pb n="3" facs="#f0001"/>
            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#k">Subterranean Noises.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The most striking in-<lb break="no"/>stance of uninterrupted subterranean
                    noise unaccom-<lb break="no"/>panied by any trace of earthquake, is the
                        ph&#x00E6;nomenon<lb break="yes"/>which is known in the Mexican territory,
                    by the name<lb break="yes"/>of &#x201C;the subterranean roaring and thundering
                        (bra-<lb break="no"/>midos y truenos subterraneos) of Guanaxuato.&#x201D;
                        This<lb break="yes"/>rich and celebrated mountain city is situated at a
                        dist-<lb break="no"/>ance from any active volcano. The noise began on the<lb
                        break="yes"/>9th January, 1784, at midnight, and lasted above a<lb
                        break="yes"/>month. I have been enabled to give a circumstantial<lb
                        break="yes"/>description of the ph&#x00E6;nomenon from the report of many<lb
                        break="yes"/>witnesses, and from the documents of the municipality<lb
                        break="yes"/>which I was permitted to make use of. From the 13th<lb
                        break="yes"/>to the 16th of January, it was as if there were heavy<lb
                        break="yes"/>storm-clouds under the feet of the inhabitants, in which<lb
                        break="yes"/>slow rolling thunder alternated with short thunder<lb
                        break="yes"/>claps. The noise ceased gradually, as it had com-<lb break="no"
                    />menced; it was confined to a small space, for it was<lb break="yes"/>not heard
                    in a bassaltic district at the distance of only<lb break="yes"/>a few miles.
                    Almost all the inhabitants were terrified<lb break="yes"/>and quitted the city,
                    in which large masses of silver<lb break="yes"/>were stored; but the most
                    courageous, when they had<lb break="yes"/>become somewhat accustomed to the
                        subterranean<lb break="yes"/>thunder, returned and fought with the bands of
                        rob-<lb break="no"/>bers who had taken possession of the treasure.
                        Neither<lb break="yes"/>at the surface, nor in mines 1,598 English feet in
                        depth,<lb break="yes"/>could the slightest trembling of the ground be
                        per-<lb break="no"/>ceived. In no part of the whole mountainous country<lb
                        break="yes"/>of Mexico had anything similar been ever known be-<lb
                        break="no"/>fore, nor has this awful ph&#x00E6;nomenon been since re-<lb
                        break="no"/>peated. Thus, as chasms in the interior of the earth<lb
                        break="yes"/>close or open, the propagation of the waves of sound<lb
                        break="yes"/>is either arrested in its progress or continued until it<lb
                        break="yes"/>reaches the ear.&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt&#x2019;s
                        Travels.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
